#------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
# FILE: opcode_buckets.lst
#
# DESCRIPTION:
#
# File to define an optional list of timing buckets for particular opcodes.
# This can be used in cases where we would like to know more about the relative
# distribution of the timings (rather than just min, max, and average).
#
# The opcodes should be listed one per line and can be either the numeric value
# or name. They are followed by a list of range delimeters (in seconds). The
# special value '*' can be used to define a default set of buckets for all
# opcodes.
#
# NOTE: We will automatically create a bucket from 0 to the first range and
#       from the last range to infinity - hoping that most opcode executions
#       won't take that long ;-).
#
# Don't configure more buckets than you really need! There is a limit of 100
# per opocde - which should be more than enough!
#
# INFORMATION:
#
# BRM performance tracing library ...
#
# REVISION:
#
# $Revision: 1.6 $
# $Author: ihargrea $
# $Date: 2020/07/16 22:39:28 $
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
#
# Example entry for QOS tracking of read object ...
#
PCM_OP_READ_OBJ    0.01  0.05  0.10  0.50  1.00  2.00  4.00  8.00  16.00
#
# Example entries for rating ...
#
PCM_OP_RATE_EVENT  0.02  0.04  0.06  0.06  0.08  1.00  2.00  4.00   8.00
#
# Example of a default bucket entry - this will apply to ALL opcodes for which
# no other bucket entry exists.
# 
*                  0.01  0.05  0.10  0.50  1.00  2.00  4.00  8.00  16.00
